WEBVTT

00:02.120 --> 00:03.662
(female announcer)
Previously on Being Mary Jane.

00:03.687 --> 00:04.896
Well,
if you're a regular viewer,

00:04.927 --> 00:07.560
you're likely aware of the tragic
death of Terrence Mitchell.

00:07.592 --> 00:09.621
This is where you will sit
when you do the interview.

00:09.644 --> 00:10.894
If I do the interview.

00:10.910 --> 00:13.355
(Lisa) I'm just a little concerned
about some of your choices.

00:13.379 --> 00:16.876
Because I don't choose
to be dateless,

00:16.907 --> 00:18.790
or sexless, or joyless?

00:18.821 --> 00:21.140
We're conducting focus groups
on all our shows.

00:21.142 --> 00:22.557
What about Mary Jane?

00:22.559 --> 00:24.848
If she doesn't test well,
she might lose her job?

00:24.850 --> 00:27.181
This information was given
to you in confidence.

00:27.183 --> 00:29.848
You're a proud Latino.
Congratulations.

00:29.850 --> 00:31.348
What is that supposed to mean?

00:31.350 --> 00:33.889
Once you take the shot,
you'll have 36 hours

00:33.891 --> 00:37.473
until you need to get back here
for the extraction.

00:37.475 --> 00:40.598
(male reporter) For those of you just
joining us, tense situation here as--

00:40.600 --> 00:42.639
it appears to be
a single gunman.

00:42.641 --> 00:44.015
African-American male,

00:44.017 --> 00:46.764
and he is holding a sign
that simply says,

00:46.766 --> 00:49.764
I am being surveilled 24/7.
And that is it.

00:49.766 --> 00:52.098
There has been no report yet
of anyone else

00:52.100 --> 00:53.140
in the vehicle with him,

00:53.142 --> 00:54.681
and we see the gun.

00:54.683 --> 00:58.307
He is holding a silver handgun
to his right temple.

00:58.309 --> 01:00.806
He is clearly a threat
to himself, at this point.

01:00.808 --> 01:04.348
The situation is getting
very desperate and uncertain.

01:04.349 --> 01:06.056
Hello.
- Kara, you watching this?

01:06.058 --> 01:08.390
(Kara) Unfortunately, yes.

01:08.392 --> 01:10.390
Duncan's covering it.
- Who?

01:10.392 --> 01:12.723
Duncan. Remember?
Our city hall guy.

01:12.725 --> 01:14.557
Cute dimples. Nice hair.

01:14.559 --> 01:17.557
Tends to miss the complexities,
but he's always ready to work,

01:17.559 --> 01:18.889
and he's already downtown, so--

01:18.891 --> 01:21.723
Oh, yeah.
Traffic's already bad.

01:21.725 --> 01:24.848
Man, all these guns.

01:24.850 --> 01:26.390
Well, at least he's only

01:26.392 --> 01:28.098
threatening
his own life, you know?

01:28.100 --> 01:29.557
Who is he?

01:29.559 --> 01:30.973
(Kara) All we have
is a name right now.

01:30.975 --> 01:33.015
His name is Brian Ellis.

01:33.017 --> 01:37.098
He works in the Atlanta office
of Durbin, McGee & Marting.

01:37.100 --> 01:39.307
He's a pretty substantial
attorney with the firm.

01:39.309 --> 01:42.056
He represents some major banks.

01:42.058 --> 01:44.473
I'm still trying to find
a way in--some kind of angle.

01:44.475 --> 01:45.681
(Mary Jane)
We got to figure most people

01:45.683 --> 01:46.682
will cover this
from the financial side.

01:46.684 --> 01:48.265
You know, crumbling economy.

01:48.267 --> 01:50.015
Pressures of Wall Street,
blah, blah, blah.

01:50.017 --> 01:51.390
Do you disagree with that?

01:51.392 --> 01:52.723
No, I mean it very well
may be true,

01:52.725 --> 01:55.473
but I always
prefer the personal approach.

01:55.475 --> 01:56.848
This is a man's life here.

01:56.850 --> 01:58.681
(Kara) Look who woke up
feeling all sentimental.

01:58.683 --> 01:59.973
It's not like I'm heartless.

01:59.975 --> 02:01.723
(Kara) Oh, you say
that like it's a bad thing.

02:01.725 --> 02:02.931
[phone beeping]

02:02.933 --> 02:04.098
No, wait. I got to--

02:04.100 --> 02:07.223
I got to go. I'll see you soon.
Bye.

02:07.225 --> 02:08.431
Good morning, Dr. Marrs.

02:08.434 --> 02:09.681
(Dr. Marrs)
How are we feeling today?

02:09.683 --> 02:11.390
Were you able to prepare
the HCG shot?

02:11.392 --> 02:14.515
Yeah. It's right here.

02:14.517 --> 02:16.390
I'm a little nervous, though.

02:16.392 --> 02:18.390
The needle is a lot bigger
than the others.

02:18.392 --> 02:21.515
You'll be fine. I have all
the confidence in the world.

02:21.517 --> 02:23.390
Now, the sole purpose
of this shot is to trigger

02:23.392 --> 02:24.806
your ovulation cycle,

02:24.808 --> 02:26.806
giving us 36 hours
until your eggs

02:26.808 --> 02:28.973
reach their ideal readiness
for extraction.

02:28.975 --> 02:32.515
Which explains my appointment
tomorrow night at 8:00 p.m.

02:32.517 --> 02:35.223
Trust me. Your eggs' maturity
determines the retrieval time.

02:35.225 --> 02:36.473
Not me.

02:36.475 --> 02:38.432
Any other questions? Concerns?

02:38.434 --> 02:40.557
No, no. I'm good.

02:40.559 --> 02:42.056
Call me if you need me.

02:42.058 --> 02:44.308
Otherwise, I'll see you
in my office tomorrow at 8:00.

02:45.309 --> 02:47.681
Okay.
Thank you for everything.

02:47.683 --> 02:50.681
[up-tempo music]

02:50.683 --> 02:58.683
♪ ♪

03:02.434 --> 03:06.808
[woman singing indistinctly]

03:08.000 --> 03:14.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

03:55.434 --> 03:56.683
This becoming a habit?

03:58.850 --> 04:00.434
Good morning to you too.

04:01.766 --> 04:04.681
Since you asked,
I could kind of use a friend.

04:04.683 --> 04:06.806
Really? What happened
to what's-her-name?

04:06.808 --> 04:08.515
How come you
can't talk to her?

04:08.517 --> 04:11.223
It's actually Ana
I need to talk about.

04:11.225 --> 04:12.723
Okay, yeah. No.

04:12.725 --> 04:14.140
I'm strong, but I--
- Seriously.

04:14.142 --> 04:15.931
I mean, I really could
use your ear right now.

04:15.933 --> 04:17.680
And you thought you should
come over here first thing

04:17.683 --> 04:19.723
in the morning
to talk to me about Ana?

04:19.725 --> 04:21.055
Way to keep it classy, dude.

04:21.058 --> 04:22.473
Can we please
not do this part?

04:22.475 --> 04:24.848
My thoughts exactly.

04:24.850 --> 04:26.973
Mary Jane, wait.
- Oh, I'm sorry.

04:26.975 --> 04:29.140
What am I waiting for, exactly?

04:29.142 --> 04:31.848
Am I waiting for you not to have
wanted her in the first place

04:31.850 --> 04:33.681
or her not to be pregnant?

04:33.683 --> 04:35.764
Listen, I can't undo
what's already done.

04:35.766 --> 04:37.348
I know.

04:37.350 --> 04:39.889
I can't, so I've just been
trying to live in the moment.

04:39.891 --> 04:41.265
Okay.

04:41.267 --> 04:44.764
All right. Last night
I had this realization.

04:44.766 --> 04:46.307
I was up late trying
to put the crib together--

04:46.309 --> 04:47.390
Really?
- I know,

04:47.392 --> 04:49.723
but that's when it hit me.

04:49.725 --> 04:51.348
I've changed everything.

04:51.350 --> 04:53.015
Just about every
aspect of my life

04:53.017 --> 04:54.681
for somebody that
I don't even know.

04:54.683 --> 04:56.223
I know. Because you already
love your baby. Got it.

04:56.225 --> 04:59.889
No. I'm not talking about
the baby, and that's my point.

04:59.891 --> 05:01.307
You should have
thought about that

05:01.309 --> 05:02.931
before you got her pregnant.

05:02.933 --> 05:05.681
Mary Jane, I'm just trying
to do the right thing.

05:05.683 --> 05:07.515
I didn't want my kid
to grow up knowing

05:07.517 --> 05:09.681
what it's like to not have
a father in the house.

05:09.683 --> 05:11.681
Very noble of you.

05:11.683 --> 05:14.683
I am trying to tell you
I feel trapped.

05:16.933 --> 05:18.681
I'm pretty sure
she feels the same way.

05:18.683 --> 05:20.348
So that's why you're here,
because you feel trapped?

05:20.350 --> 05:21.434
No.

05:23.559 --> 05:25.056
I'm here because
neither one of us

05:25.058 --> 05:26.681
is living the life
we're supposed to be living.

05:26.683 --> 05:28.432
And yet that still
doesn't change the fact

05:28.434 --> 05:30.973
that she's having
your baby, does it?

05:30.975 --> 05:32.848
Does it?

05:32.850 --> 05:35.390
So at this point, I don't really
know what more you want from me.

05:35.392 --> 05:39.098
I want you to tell me
it's not too late for us.

05:39.100 --> 05:40.683
I really wish I could, but...

05:42.517 --> 05:44.515
Right now, I--

05:44.517 --> 05:45.683
I just can't.

05:51.766 --> 05:53.683
Can you move your car, please?

05:59.559 --> 06:00.973
(Duncan)
If ever there was an example

06:00.975 --> 06:03.390
that success and happiness
aren't one and the same,

06:03.392 --> 06:05.181
this is certainly it.

06:05.183 --> 06:07.681
A graduate of Columbia
University, Brian Ellis

06:07.683 --> 06:10.015
went on to finish tops
in his class at Yale Law School

06:10.017 --> 06:12.681
before joining the Atlanta
office of the prominent law firm

06:12.683 --> 06:14.223
of Durbin, McGee & Marting

06:14.225 --> 06:15.848
where,
according to several sources,

06:15.850 --> 06:18.889
he appeared to be
on the fast track to partner.

06:18.891 --> 06:22.806
With so much going on for
this married father of two,

06:22.808 --> 06:25.889
one can't help but wonder,
what pushed him this close

06:25.891 --> 06:27.015
to the edge?

06:27.017 --> 06:28.764
For SNC, I'm Duncan Isaac.

06:28.766 --> 06:30.473
Mark, back to you.

06:30.475 --> 06:32.015
Mark, baby, listen.

06:32.017 --> 06:33.806
We're gonna stick with
the Wall Street angle, okay?

06:33.808 --> 06:35.390
I'll get you something
as soon as I have it.

06:35.392 --> 06:37.723
More about Durbin,
McGee & Marting.

06:37.725 --> 06:40.432
With nearly 1,400 attorneys,
it is one of the largest...

06:40.434 --> 06:42.015
Hey.
- Hey.

06:42.017 --> 06:44.806
Look, I think we need to look
into the effect of stress

06:44.808 --> 06:47.265
on the African-American family
in the 21st century,

06:47.267 --> 06:49.764
as well as suicide rates

06:49.766 --> 06:52.473
among African-American men
in corporate America.

06:52.475 --> 06:55.015
Wait, this is a story
about an overworked attorney.

06:55.017 --> 06:57.265
What does him being black have
anything to do with anything?

06:57.267 --> 06:59.015
Terrence Mitchell,
just a few months ago.

06:59.017 --> 07:01.348
Successful black man.
Committed suicide.

07:01.350 --> 07:03.181
Hip-hop pioneer Chris Lighty.

07:03.183 --> 07:04.348
Successful black man.

07:04.350 --> 07:05.557
Committed suicide.

07:05.559 --> 07:07.681
Record executive
Shakir Stewart.

07:07.683 --> 07:09.681
Successful black man.
Committed suicide.

07:09.683 --> 07:11.140
Rap artist Capital Steez.

07:11.142 --> 07:13.265
Professional football player
Kenny McKinley.

07:13.267 --> 07:14.390
Actor Lee Thompson Young.

07:14.392 --> 07:15.848
All successful black men.

07:15.850 --> 07:17.889
All committed suicide.

07:17.891 --> 07:20.265
Come on.

07:20.267 --> 07:21.681
Go. What are you waiting for?

07:21.683 --> 07:23.015
I'm not sure
what I'm looking for.

07:23.017 --> 07:24.931
Black men, and suicide rates,
and trends--

07:24.933 --> 07:27.265
In the last five years.

07:27.267 --> 07:28.681
Glad you could join us.

07:28.683 --> 07:30.681
That guy
and Terrence Mitchell--

07:30.683 --> 07:32.223
I mean those are
our best and brightest.

07:32.225 --> 07:34.432
Wait--oh.

07:34.434 --> 07:35.975
Give me two minutes.

07:39.517 --> 07:41.015
This is a surprise.

07:41.017 --> 07:43.140
(Sheldon) I assume you've
been following this.

07:43.142 --> 07:45.723
Any interest in an exclusive?
- Always.

07:45.725 --> 07:48.056
(Sheldon) No one can know I'm involved.

07:48.058 --> 07:49.265
No exceptions.

07:49.267 --> 07:50.931
What's one more
secret in my life?

07:50.933 --> 07:53.265
And here I thought
you were an open book.

07:53.267 --> 07:55.140
Hardly.
- Okay. Hang tight.

07:55.142 --> 07:56.723
(Sheldon) They'll probably try
to discredit him somehow.

07:56.725 --> 07:57.724
Once they do,
I'll call you back.

07:57.726 --> 08:00.848
Who's "they?" Hello?

08:00.850 --> 08:03.434
(woman)
Sir, please put the gun down.

08:04.933 --> 08:06.348
(man) I've got a visual.

08:06.350 --> 08:07.889
This can all work
out peacefully.

08:07.891 --> 08:09.056
Sorry.

08:09.058 --> 08:10.764
That was my mom.

08:10.766 --> 08:12.223
Everything okay?
- Yeah, yeah, yeah. She's fine.

08:12.225 --> 08:14.432
No, I meant with you.

08:14.434 --> 08:16.390
No, no. I'm good.
- Yeah?

08:16.392 --> 08:17.681
(man) The firm just
released a statement,

08:17.683 --> 08:19.056
and AP's going wide with a quote

08:19.058 --> 08:20.681
from an anonymous source.
- What have we got?

08:20.683 --> 08:22.015
Duncan's going
live with it right now.

08:22.017 --> 08:24.015
Okay.

08:24.017 --> 08:25.723
Duncan, we good?
- Rock and roll.

08:25.725 --> 08:28.181
Okay, Mark,
we just got some breaking news,

08:28.183 --> 08:30.265
so I'm gonna have you throw it
over to Duncan on my cue, okay?

08:30.267 --> 08:31.141
(Mark) Ready to roll.

08:31.143 --> 08:32.347
Mark, here we go.

08:32.350 --> 08:35.722
On three, two, one.

08:35.725 --> 08:37.390
With breaking news,

08:37.392 --> 08:39.972
we now return to Duncan Isaacs
live on the scene.

08:39.975 --> 08:41.889
Duncan?
- Thanks, Mark.

08:41.890 --> 08:44.390
SNC has just received
a statement released moments ago

08:44.392 --> 08:46.015
by the law firm that says,

08:46.017 --> 08:48.848
and I quote, "While all of us"
at Durbin, McGee & Marting

08:48.850 --> 08:50.973
continue to hope and pray
for a safe resolution

08:50.975 --> 08:53.681
to this ongoing situation,
we are not at liberty

08:53.683 --> 08:56.473
to reveal any specific details
about the party involved

08:56.475 --> 08:59.432
or the circumstances that have
led to this tragic event.

08:59.434 --> 09:00.848
And in a separate statement,

09:00.850 --> 09:02.764
this one coming
from the Associated Press,

09:02.766 --> 09:05.432
citing an anonymous source close
to Mr. Ellis, we've learned,

09:05.434 --> 09:06.889
and again I quote,

09:06.891 --> 09:08.056
Though we've seen Brian

09:08.058 --> 09:09.848
exhibit erratic behavior
in the past,

09:09.850 --> 09:11.931
coupled with unexpected bouts
of hostility,

09:11.933 --> 09:13.557
we were unaware, until today,

09:13.559 --> 09:16.181
that he suffers from a mild
form of schizophrenia,

09:16.183 --> 09:19.515
a disease for which he recently
began seeking treatment.

09:19.517 --> 09:21.557
I'm Duncan Isaac.

09:21.559 --> 09:23.265
Unbelievable.
- Thank you, Duncan.

09:23.267 --> 09:26.098
The firm, founded in 1904,
has long been...

09:26.100 --> 09:27.889
How did you know
that would happen?

09:27.891 --> 09:30.307
I never discuss business
over the phone.

09:30.309 --> 09:31.848
Where can I meet you, then?

09:31.850 --> 09:34.681
(Sheldon) At my home, as long
as that's okay with you.

09:34.683 --> 09:37.223
This situation requires
a bit of discretion.

09:37.225 --> 09:38.889
Are you always this cautious?

09:38.891 --> 09:41.348
(Sheldon) I try to be.

09:41.350 --> 09:43.056
If you're still interested,
I'll have a car

09:43.058 --> 09:45.681
waiting outside
your studio after your show.

09:45.683 --> 09:46.889
(Mary Jane) I'll see you
in a few hours, then.

09:46.891 --> 09:49.473
Great. Looking forward to it.

09:49.475 --> 09:51.848
(Mark) And its dependency
on financial service--

09:51.850 --> 09:53.015
Oh!

09:53.017 --> 09:54.140
Oh, my God!

09:54.142 --> 09:55.598
Oh, my God. Cut it. Cut it.

09:55.600 --> 09:57.473
Jesus. Who fired that?

09:57.475 --> 09:58.973
Was that the police?
- Mark?

09:58.975 --> 10:00.015
Yeah.
- Say something.

10:00.017 --> 10:01.432
Anything.

10:01.434 --> 10:03.268
Mark, say something.
- This is a sad day...

10:05.225 --> 10:08.181
[elegant piano music]

10:08.183 --> 10:09.473
♪ ♪

10:09.475 --> 10:11.140
Thank you.

10:11.142 --> 10:13.723
(Kara) You want to chase stories?
That's fine.

10:13.725 --> 10:15.307
I just don't
understand why you insist

10:15.309 --> 10:16.973
on keeping me in the dark.

10:16.975 --> 10:18.681
(Mary Jane) Well, because
my source asked for privacy.

10:18.683 --> 10:21.307
I assumed
you could respect that.

10:21.309 --> 10:25.307
And I thought we were a team
fighting these fights together.

10:25.309 --> 10:29.432
We are, and as soon as I
know more, I'll fill you in.

10:29.434 --> 10:31.056
But not just yet, right?

10:31.058 --> 10:32.515
Okay.

10:32.517 --> 10:33.474
Goodbye.

10:33.476 --> 10:41.475
♪ ♪

10:47.600 --> 10:50.223
Hello? Anyone home?

10:50.225 --> 10:51.307
Come on in.

10:51.309 --> 10:53.473
Sorry. Excuse my manners.

10:53.475 --> 10:55.223
I'm just in the middle
of a really important step.

10:55.225 --> 10:56.265
Oh, gosh, should I
take my shoes off?

10:56.267 --> 10:58.223
As you like.

10:58.225 --> 11:00.307
I hope you're hungry.
I'm making etouffee.

11:00.309 --> 11:01.683
It's my grandmother's recipe.

11:03.058 --> 11:05.764
It's a little bit more...

11:05.766 --> 11:07.683
Creole than it is Cajun.

11:08.891 --> 11:10.473
Try it.

11:10.475 --> 11:11.889
Mmm.

11:11.891 --> 11:14.559
Delicious, but I'm not
here for the food, am I?

11:18.891 --> 11:20.058
Please.

11:27.309 --> 11:28.848
Sit.

11:28.850 --> 11:30.390
Relax.

11:30.392 --> 11:32.931
Life, like a great etouffee,

11:32.933 --> 11:36.348
requires time and patience.

11:36.350 --> 11:38.889
(Mary Jane) Yeah.
Lately, I hate to admit it,

11:38.891 --> 11:41.432
but I seem to be
in short supply of both,

11:41.434 --> 11:43.515
so, that being said,

11:43.517 --> 11:44.973
today a man took his own life,

11:44.975 --> 11:48.723
and you led me to believe
that you know why.

11:48.725 --> 11:50.181
I do.

11:50.183 --> 11:52.390
But sadly for you,
now that he's dead,

11:52.392 --> 11:54.056
God rest his soul,

11:54.058 --> 11:57.806
your exclusive may be
slightly more than a head start.

11:57.808 --> 11:59.098
Especially after
they start going

11:59.100 --> 12:00.181
through his computer
and his files.

12:00.183 --> 12:02.764
Who is "they?"

12:02.766 --> 12:05.181
Patience and time.

12:05.183 --> 12:06.099
We'll get to it.

12:06.101 --> 12:07.434
I promise.

12:09.683 --> 12:13.348
Frankly, I'm surprised that it
doesn't happen more often,

12:13.350 --> 12:17.181
what with all the corporate
deception in the workplace.

12:17.183 --> 12:18.931
Especially if you're
a black man.

12:18.933 --> 12:20.557
Well, we all have pressures
to deal with.

12:20.559 --> 12:23.723
Yes, we all have pressures
to deal with, of course.

12:23.725 --> 12:25.889
But our plight

12:25.891 --> 12:28.681
is a particularly unique one,

12:28.683 --> 12:30.681
would you not agree?

12:30.683 --> 12:31.806
Yeah. I suppose.

12:31.808 --> 12:33.056
Sure.

12:33.058 --> 12:35.681
Do you mind if I record this?

12:35.683 --> 12:38.265
I do.
- Okay.

12:38.267 --> 12:40.681
Did you know that
etouffee in French

12:40.683 --> 12:44.931
literally translates
to "suffocate?"

12:44.933 --> 12:47.015
To smother.
- What's your point?

12:47.017 --> 12:48.933
I'm guessing
you're trying to make one.

12:50.808 --> 12:53.515
My point is that black men

12:53.517 --> 12:55.848
in America today,

12:55.850 --> 12:57.181
like Brian Ellis,

12:57.183 --> 12:59.307
have been smothered

12:59.309 --> 13:01.764
literally their whole lives.

13:01.766 --> 13:05.723
Smothered as they
clawed their way up the ranks.

13:05.725 --> 13:08.140
Smothered by corporate greed.

13:08.142 --> 13:10.015
Smothered by racism.

13:10.017 --> 13:11.473
By oppression.

13:11.475 --> 13:13.015
Smothered by hatred.

13:13.017 --> 13:15.683
Smothered by fear.

13:17.309 --> 13:18.723
Smothered by a system

13:18.725 --> 13:20.891
that truly never wanted
to see them succeed.

13:22.766 --> 13:24.017
And why do you think that is?

13:26.975 --> 13:29.806
Jealousy.

13:29.808 --> 13:32.557
Obama's walk was inspired
by Michael Jordan's dunk,

13:32.559 --> 13:36.307
was inspired
by John Coltrane's solo,

13:36.309 --> 13:39.848
by Malcolm X's thoughts.

13:39.850 --> 13:41.140
Can you drive the car
straight?

13:41.142 --> 13:42.517
Because I have low blood sugar.

13:45.267 --> 13:47.723
Black men represent freedom,

13:47.725 --> 13:50.848
and that's what they're
trying to squash.

13:50.850 --> 13:54.015
So many black men, myself
included, have been surveilled.

13:54.017 --> 13:55.223
Have been bullied.

13:55.225 --> 13:58.848
Have been pushed
until we find ourselves

13:58.850 --> 14:04.683
standing out on a ledge
with nowhere to go but down.

14:08.309 --> 14:11.889
You made it clear that you
wanted to tell my story.

14:11.891 --> 14:15.265
The story of who I am,
of where I've come from.

14:15.267 --> 14:16.515
What I've been through.

14:16.517 --> 14:19.683
What I've endured
to find success.

14:21.517 --> 14:24.223
This is my story,

14:24.225 --> 14:27.098
or at least it's as close to it
as I'm currently

14:27.100 --> 14:28.309
willing to share.

14:30.850 --> 14:31.850
Okay.

14:33.434 --> 14:34.515
You know,
it's rarely discussed,

14:34.517 --> 14:36.723
but the life
of a black man today

14:36.725 --> 14:39.265
is significantly more difficult

14:39.267 --> 14:41.473
than any other
single demographic.

14:41.475 --> 14:44.140
Well, except for that
of a black woman.

14:44.142 --> 14:45.434
Including that

14:48.017 --> 14:49.098
Is that so?

14:49.100 --> 14:50.225
Most definitely.

14:52.350 --> 14:53.681
I'm not sure if you're trying

14:53.683 --> 14:56.181
to pick a fight
with me or offend me.

14:56.183 --> 14:58.681
Neither.
I'm just trying to make a point.

14:58.683 --> 15:03.390
So are you saying
that black women have not been

15:03.392 --> 15:06.015
smothered by American
ideals and expectations?

15:06.017 --> 15:07.931
That we have not been
surveilled, pushed down,

15:07.933 --> 15:09.681
bullied, and belittled
by society?

15:09.683 --> 15:10.973
Is that what you're
trying to say?

15:10.975 --> 15:12.223
No, I'm not--
- No, no, no. Let me finish,

15:12.225 --> 15:14.015
because, truth be told,

15:14.017 --> 15:18.223
not only has society tried
to smother black women,

15:18.225 --> 15:20.432
we've also been smothered
by the very black men

15:20.434 --> 15:23.723
who claim to defend our honor.

15:23.725 --> 15:26.098
Least you guys have
someone to go home to.

15:26.100 --> 15:27.265
Chit-chat with.

15:27.267 --> 15:29.348
Talk out your troubles,

15:29.350 --> 15:31.681
but who the hell
takes care of us?

15:31.683 --> 15:35.223
Who's left to love
the black woman, hmm?

15:35.225 --> 15:36.681
You want to talk hard?

15:36.683 --> 15:39.056
Try finding an educated
black man in America.

15:39.058 --> 15:41.098
Now that-- that's difficult.

15:41.100 --> 15:43.265
No, that's a myth.

15:43.267 --> 15:46.681
There's nearly 1.5 million
black men in college,

15:46.683 --> 15:49.098
compared to 840,000
in the prison system.

15:49.100 --> 15:51.098
That wasn't the correlation
I was making.

15:51.100 --> 15:55.348
In my opinion, that'd be
a foolish one to make.

15:55.350 --> 15:57.764
But since you
brought it up, yes.

15:57.766 --> 16:00.015
Black men are in college.

16:00.017 --> 16:04.223
Community college, not
the fiercely competitive ones

16:04.225 --> 16:05.973
that you and I attended.

16:05.975 --> 16:07.098
Those are the men
I'm talking about.

16:07.100 --> 16:08.931
Where are they?

16:08.933 --> 16:12.681
Stop me if I'm wrong,
but don't black women make up

16:12.683 --> 16:16.390
2/3 of all African-American
bachelor degrees?

16:16.392 --> 16:18.681
70% of all master's degrees?

16:18.683 --> 16:21.265
60% of all doctorates?

16:21.267 --> 16:24.015
I mean, I'm not naïve
to understanding

16:24.017 --> 16:26.764
the systemic complexities
of the journey,

16:26.766 --> 16:28.681
but come on.

16:28.683 --> 16:32.681
At the end of the day,
our men aren't there.

16:32.683 --> 16:36.348
So, you think this is hard?

16:36.350 --> 16:38.350
Living up in this massive house?

16:40.058 --> 16:43.056
Try being a single
black woman in America.

16:43.058 --> 16:44.559
That's hard.

16:47.517 --> 16:49.140
Yeah.

16:49.142 --> 16:51.056
You're sexy.
- Okay.

16:51.058 --> 16:54.723
See, that's the belittling
that I was just talking about.

16:54.725 --> 16:57.265
Why is it that men
automatically have to reduce us

16:57.267 --> 16:58.473
down to our sexuality?

16:58.475 --> 17:00.557
Why can't you-- excuse me--

17:00.559 --> 17:03.889
hear me and not
try to minimalize me

17:03.891 --> 17:06.681
down to a pair of tits and ass?

17:06.683 --> 17:09.432
I thought you were
a little smarter than that.

17:09.434 --> 17:12.307
I do hear you, Mary Jane.

17:12.309 --> 17:15.348
That's why I think you're sexy.

17:15.349 --> 17:18.432
I forgot I was
dealing with a lawyer.

17:18.434 --> 17:20.931
You know what I find most
attractive about you

17:20.933 --> 17:23.015
is your passion,

17:23.017 --> 17:25.181
your wit,

17:25.183 --> 17:29.265
your perceptions on life.

17:29.267 --> 17:31.515
That's why I called you.

17:31.517 --> 17:35.098
Not because of your full lips,
your high cheekbones,

17:35.100 --> 17:37.891
or those soulful
brown eyes you have.

17:39.975 --> 17:44.140
I called you because you
are the absolute best person

17:44.142 --> 17:45.933
to share this story
with the world.

17:49.142 --> 17:51.681
Can you show me which way
to your powder room, please?

17:51.683 --> 17:53.723
It's the first door on the left.

17:53.725 --> 17:55.309
Thank you.
- Yeah, sure.

18:10.183 --> 18:11.806
All that being said,

18:11.808 --> 18:14.058
your ass is not bad, either.

18:47.183 --> 18:49.515
[line ringing]

18:49.517 --> 18:52.764
Hello. Is Dr. Marrs available?

18:52.766 --> 18:54.931
Oh.

18:54.933 --> 18:56.181
Maybe you can help me, then.

18:56.183 --> 18:58.223
I'm one of Dr. Marrs' patients,

18:58.225 --> 19:00.681
and I just experienced,

19:00.683 --> 19:03.307
like a--

19:03.309 --> 19:04.681
like a discharge.

19:04.683 --> 19:07.140
No, no. More of, like, a...

19:07.142 --> 19:08.891
massive orgasm.

19:11.683 --> 19:14.098
No. Like,
totally out of the blue.

19:14.100 --> 19:17.390
I just took it this morning.

19:17.392 --> 19:18.848
Oh, so it's totally normal?

19:18.850 --> 19:21.307
Okay. Okay. No, no, no.

19:21.309 --> 19:23.181
No, that's all I wanted.

19:23.183 --> 19:24.806
Yeah. No, thank you.

19:24.808 --> 19:26.681
I'll see him when I get
in the office tomorrow.

19:26.683 --> 19:28.265
All right.

19:28.267 --> 19:29.557
Bye-bye.

